text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!Chinese Accent Discrimination%0a%0a:Author: MarkC%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aExploring the questionable /l/ and /ɹ/ stereotype in Chinese accents%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0a'''Trigger Warning: racism against Chinese, slurs'''%0a%0aVideo: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rRspB7EJzBA&ab_channel=Alan55%0a%0aAs indicated by the context of the South Park video, the dialect in question that is being mocked is the "Chinese" dialect. In the video, the words hello /həloʊ/ and please /pliz/ are being satirically pronounced with a mock "Chinese accent" as /həɹoʊ/ and /pɹiz/ where the /l/ consonant is being substituted by the /ɹ/ consonant. %0a%0aThis is a very common stereotype associated with Chinese speakers of English in America but interestingly enough, it seems to have no factual origin. In both standard Mandarin (Putonghua) and Cantonese, the /l/ phoneme exists in the onset of syllables[1, 2]. Thus, there is no reason to suspect native Chinese speakers to have problems with pronouncing the /l/ sound in the onset position such as in the words "hello" and "please". In my personal experience interacting with native Chinese speakers speaking English, I have never heard anyone substitute /l/ with /ɹ/ in a syllable onset. When I asked my parents, who are native Chinese speakers, they also agreed that they didn't think Chinese speakers speaking English would have problem pronouncing the /l/ sound in the onset.%0a%0aI suspect the origin of this incorrect stereotype has to do with mixing up the English dialects of native Chinese speakers with that of Japanese speakers. In Japanese, /l/ and /ɹ/ are not phonemes and the phoneme that most closely resembles those sounds is the alveolar flap /ɾ/[3]. Thus it is reasonable to think that Japanese speakers could have problems pronouncing /l/ in English, and substitute it with /ɹ/ which could be perceived as /ɹ/ by native English speakers (Another possibility being just mixing up the /l/ and /ɹ/ sounds as they are allophones in Japanese). Over time perhaps, the stereotype of Japanese English speakers expanded to include the English dialects of other East Asian countries. %0a%0aThe misattribution of the /l/ and /ɹ/ stereotype to Chinese speakers is indicative of a problematic pattern of discrimination in America: that of lumping together the wide and diverse cultures in Asia into one homogenous category. The ignorant reduction of separate cultures into a single, giant blob simply considered as "outsider" is extremely damaging to the personal identities of many Asian minorities in America.   %0a%0a[1] https://www.mustgo.com/worldlanguages/mandarin/%0a%0a[2] https://corpus.eduhk.hk/mandarin_pronunciation/?page_id=36%0a%0a[3] https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA/Japanese%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210506-040314-457180#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!/l/ and /ɹ/ in Korean %0a-> - shreya_r%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aAnother language where this stereotype could come from is Korean. In Korean, /l/ and /ɹ/ are represented by the same letter of the alphabet, so when writing words using the Korean alphabet, both of these sounds would be represented by that letter. Therefore, when learning how to pronounce words in English, native Korean speakers might pronounce both sounds the same in all contexts, either using /l/ in place of every /ɹ/ or vice versa, because both would be written the same in their phonetic alphabet (for example, "rake" and "lake" are spelled identically in Hangul). Because there is no distinction between the sounds in Korean, native speakers would not be accustomed to differentiating between them. This may also contribute to a stereotype of East Asians in general not knowing how to differentiate between the two sounds, especially since many Americans are unable to tell the difference between Chinese, Japanese, and Korean.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210506-040314-457180#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: F:)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
