diff:1619927837:1619927837:=1,80d0%0a%3c (:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c [[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%3c %0a%3c !Chinese Accent Discrimination%0a%3c %0a%3c :Author: MarkC%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Summary:''' \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Exploring the questionable /l/ and /r/ stereotype in Chinese accents%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c *Trigger Warning: racism against Chinese, slurs%0a%3c Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rRspB7EJzBA&ab_channel=Alan55%0a%3c %0a%3c As indicated by the context of the South Park video, the dialect in question that is being mocked is the "Chinese" dialect. In the video, the words hello /həloʊ/ and please /pliz/ are being satirically pronounced with a mock "Chinese accent" as /həroʊ/ and /priz/ where the /l/ consonant is being substituted by the /r/ consonant. %0a%3c %0a%3c This is a very common stereotype associated with Chinese speakers of English in America but interestingly enough, it seems to have no factual origin. In both standard Mandarin (Putonghua) and Cantonese, the /l/ phoneme exists in the onset of syllables[1, 2]. Thus, there is no reason to suspect native Chinese speakers to have problems with pronouncing the /l/ sound in the onset position such as in the words "hello" and "please". In my personal experience interacting with native Chinese speakers speaking English, I have never heard anyone substitute /l/ with /r/ in a syllable onset. When I asked my parents, who are native Chinese speakers, they also agreed that they didn't think Chinese speakers speaking English would have problem pronouncing the /l/ sound in the onset.%0a%3c %0a%3c I suspect the origin of this incorrect stereotype has to do with mixing up the English dialects of native Chinese speakers with that of Japanese speakers. In Japanese, /l/ and /r/ are not phonemes and the phoneme that most closely resembles those sounds is the alveolar flap /ɾ/ [3]. Thus it is reasonable to think that Japanese speakers could have problems pronouncing /l/ in English, and substitute it with /ɾ/ which could be perceived as /r/ by native English speakers (Another possibility being just mixing up the /l/ and /r/ sounds as they are allophones in Japanese). Over time perhaps, the stereotype of Japanese English speakers expanded to include the English dialects of other East Asian countries. %0a%3c %0a%3c The misattribution of the /l/ and /r/ stereotype to Chinese speakers is indicative of a problematic pattern of discrimination in America: that of lumping together the wide and diverse cultures in Asia into one homogenous category. The ignorant reduction of separate cultures into a single, giant blob simply considered as "outsider" is extremely damaging to the personal identities of many Asian minorities in America.   %0a%3c %0a%3c [1] https://www.mustgo.com/worldlanguages/mandarin/%0a%3c [2] https://corpus.eduhk.hk/mandarin_pronunciation/?page_id=36%0a%3c [3] https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA/Japanese%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: F:)%0a%3c (:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)%0a\ No newline at e